Inside Instagram‚Äôs reinvention
How Kevin Systrom got over minimalism and snapped into building mode.

  
    by

    
Kurt Wagner


        Jan 23, 2017,  6:30am EST
      











          
            tweet
          
        






          
            share
          
        






          
            Linkedin
          
        




Toward the tail end of 2015, Kevin Systrom, the CEO of Instagram, came to a realization: The photo-sharing app he had founded five years earlier was straying too far from its roots. 
Instagram was growing, yes, and finally generating some serious ad dollars ‚Äî which Facebook had been waiting for since it bought the company for $1 billion back in 2012. 
But its user base was also growing, and it wasn‚Äôt all good growth: Instagram feeds that were once dominated by photos from friends and family members were becoming more impersonal. 
Brands, celebrities and publishers had arrived en masse, and with them the pressure to capture and share that perfect photo ‚Äî the one that made you and your weekend hiking adventure look as cool as humanly possible ‚Äî had escalated. User feeds were riddled with what some saw as over-produced or inauthentic depictions of people‚Äôs lives. The feed was becoming a digital game of keeping up with the Joneses. 
‚ÄúIt became a place where people kept raising the bar on themselves in terms of the quality of what they had to achieve to post,‚Äù explained Kevin Weil, Instagram‚Äôs head of product, who has been working to fix this problem since joining Instagram from Twitter in early 2016. ‚ÄúWe didn‚Äôt want that.‚Äù
That pressure on users led to pressure internally at Instagram. Users started sharing less frequently, according to a June 2016 report from The Information. And Snapchat, the hot messaging app from LA that Facebook tried to buy but couldn‚Äôt, was offering young people the kind of experience that Instagram was not: A low-pressure way to share photos and videos that don‚Äôt stick around online.  
In April of last year, a study from investment bank Piper Jaffray found that Snapchat had surpassed Instagram as the ‚Äúmost important‚Äù social network for teenagers, a title Instagram had held the previous two years. Another study by RBC found the same, that teens would choose Snapchat over Instagram as the one social network they‚Äôd choose if they were trapped on a desert island. 
Instagram needed to evolve. Systrom did that by looking backward: He refocused the company around priorities he says Instagram held in its early days.
‚ÄúYour connections with your friends and your family are the thing that make Instagram work,‚Äù Systrom, 33, explained from Facebook‚Äôs Menlo Park, Calif., headquarters late last month. ‚ÄúAll the data supports that if you follow more friends and engage with your friends, your activity goes through the roof. If you just follow more celebrity content or more interest-based content, that doesn‚Äôt move the needle at all.‚Äù
‚ÄúYour connections with your friends and your family are the thing that make Instagram work.‚Äù
That realization led to a massive product push in 2016 designed to make Instagram more authentic, encouraging users to share with friends in places outside of the traditional feed.
The list of major updates since May include:


Instagram Stories ‚Äî Montages of photos and short videos that users can share with their followers. Stories expire after 24 hours. 

A feed ranking algorithm ‚Äî A computer model that surfaces the posts Instagram thinks you‚Äôll like, not just the most recently published content.  

Live video broadcasting ‚Äî The ability to stream live video directly to your followers, who in turn can send you messages while they watch. The video feeds disappear after they‚Äôve ended. 

Ephemeral messages ‚Äî A new messaging feature that erases the photos or videos you send friends after they‚Äôve been opened. 

Ask Systrom for the ‚Äúaha‚Äù moment that prompted such a rampant product revival and he won‚Äôt be able to name one. He won‚Äôt comment on Instagram‚Äôs sharing decline (though he doesn‚Äôt deny it either), and says Snapchat ‚Äúmotivate[s] us in the sense that I think that they‚Äôre really innovative.‚Äù
Not exactly a rallying cry.
Instead, Systrom chalks up Instagram‚Äôs busy year to a combination of changes, both structural and philosophical.
For starters, Instagram got much bigger.* The company‚Äôs engineering team, which had long been run by co-founder Mike Krieger, hired a new leader in fall of 2015: Jim Everingham, a former Yahoo VP who oversaw engineering for Yahoo‚Äôs homepage. Then Everingham went on a hiring spree, doubling his team‚Äôs size last year to more than 200 people. (Krieger is still at Instagram as CTO, but focused more on big picture issues.)
The product organization grew, too. The key hire was Weil, the former product boss and longtime exec at Twitter who oversaw the company‚Äôs ad products through the IPO. Weil was known inside Twitter as a good operator; he left the company in early 2016 after a year and a half as Twitter‚Äôs highest-ranking product executive. 
Weil now has the same role at Instagram, where he‚Äôs tasked with turning Systrom‚Äôs visions into reality. The duo have known each other for a decade ‚Äî Weil‚Äôs wife Elizabeth went to Stanford with Systrom ‚Äî and Weil says getting the chance to work with Systrom at Instagram was a huge draw. 
‚Äú[Systrom is] absolutely one of the best product thinkers I‚Äôve ever met,‚Äù Weil said in December from the company‚Äôs new office, a three-story complex a short bike ride from Facebook‚Äôs main headquarters. ‚ÄúProbably the best I‚Äôve ever worked with.‚Äù 
Even with that growth, Instagram is still small compared to its peers. It has just north of 450 employees despite a product with 600 million monthly users and 300 million daily users. Twitter, for comparison, has more than 3,500 employees for 317 million monthly users, and Snapchat has more than 1,500 employees for a daily user base half the size of Instagram‚Äôs.
That‚Äôs not a completely fair comparison: Instagram has the luxury of tapping into Facebook resources like data centers, content moderation teams and advertising technology ‚Äî things that its competitors have to build and support on their own.
But Instagram is still taking advantage of its nimble staff.
‚ÄúYou can turn the ship much more quickly with smaller teams,‚Äù Weil explained. ‚ÄúWhen we decide to do something, the time difference between us making the decision and doing it is very small. And that‚Äôs different if you have a multi-thousand person organization.‚Äù
Weil says that Instagram Stories, the company‚Äôs most significant product launch of the year and a direct copy of a Snapchat feature with the same name, was the first big product he worked on after joining Systrom at Instagram. Concept to launch took just four months. (Of course, it‚Äôs also faster to launch a product that‚Äôs nearly identical to one already on the market.) 
 








An Instagram story from Curbed. 
Vox Media / Curbed



Stories lets users share with their friends a montage of photos and videos that expire after 24 hours. The feature has been a hit with Instagram‚Äôs users: 150 million people use Stories every day. That‚Äôs as many people as Snapchat‚Äôs entire user base. 
One reason people likely use Stories is that you can‚Äôt really miss them. Instagram added the new feature at the very top of the home screen, so it‚Äôs the first thing you see whenever you open the app. (In Snapchat, the app opens directly to the camera, prompting you to share something, but not necessarily something to Stories.)
‚ÄúThere‚Äôs no more bold move you could have made,‚Äù Weil said about the new product‚Äôs location. ‚ÄúAnd [it happened] without the kind of existential debate, because the founder and the CEO says this is the problem we need to solve.‚Äù 
Stories, for example, was never tested outside of Facebook‚Äôs walls. In other words, it was a feature Instagram‚Äôs top brass wanted, regardless of whether or not its user base was on board. 
Systrom cites Stories, Instagram‚Äôs ranked feed and even its decision to abandon square-only photos back in August 2015 as examples of ‚Äúfalse constraints‚Äù that were holding Instagram back.
‚Äú[There was] a change in philosophy internally of not being too precious about what got us here,‚Äù Systrom explained. ‚ÄúI learned a lesson from watching other companies who held onto things too long. If you look at the history of companies that have succeeded and the ones that have failed, there‚Äôs a pretty clear pattern that the ones that have succeeded typically morph every couple of years into something new. And that change is fairly uncomfortable.‚Äù
‚Äú[There was] a change in philosophy internally of not being too precious about what got us here.‚Äù
Stories, in particular, was a change targeting the pressure around sharing that Instagram executives had noticed in late 2015. Stories disappear after 24 hours, meaning the bar for what qualifies as ‚Äúpost-worthy‚Äù is usually much lower on Stories than what you‚Äôll find in your feed. It‚Äôs a lot of the same stuff ‚Äî food shots, sunsets, selfies ‚Äî just less manicured. 
Instagram doesn‚Äôt deny that it borrowed the idea for Stories. Weil says the feature was ‚Äúbuilt on a format that Snapchat invented. It‚Äôs because they were solving the same problem. It‚Äôs a format, [and] we believe that format will be universal.‚Äù 
Admitting to borrowing an idea is one thing, but neither Weil nor Systrom will admit that Snapchat‚Äôs rise in popularity is pushing Instagram to move faster. (Multiple former Facebook employees say that Snapchat is indeed a driving force ‚Äî and Instagram‚Äôs spate of very similar product launches seems to confirm the same.) 
‚ÄúThey motivate us in the sense that I think that they‚Äôre really innovative. I think that they execute really well,‚Äù Systrom said. ‚ÄúI think we run different companies and I think we have different goals in mind, but we share a lot of the same aspirations.‚Äù
Casual sharing is certainly one of those aspirations. Instagram also launched disappearing private messages, another Snapchat innovation. And when you create a live video broadcast on Instagram, the video disappears as soon as the broadcast ends. It doesn‚Äôt stick around as part of your profile. 
These kinds of changes seem to be working for Instagram. The company added its last 100 million users in just six months, the fastest growth rate in company history. The sharing problem from 2015 seems to be fixed, too. 
‚ÄúIn the last couple months, with ranked feed and Stories, people are sharing more now than ever on a per-person basis, and more people are sharing [in] total,‚Äù Systrom said, without providing actual numbers. ‚ÄúWe have more people sharing every single day than ever before.‚Äù 

  
That‚Äôs good news for Facebook, which seems to be betting on Instagram to not only fend off Snapchat but boost Facebook‚Äôs sales.
Instagram‚Äôs ad revenue has become more crucial to Facebook, which is starting to run out of places in its News Feed to put advertisements. Instagram, though, is still just ramping up a business that analysts think could be huge. 
Research firm eMarketer estimates that nearly three quarters of U.S. companies over 100 employees will use Instagram for marketing in 2017, more than the number that will do the same on Twitter. Credit Suisse, meanwhile, estimated back in April that Instagram would bring in more than $3 billion in revenue in 2016, though other analyst firms offered more conservative estimates. (Facebook doesn‚Äôt yet break out Instagram‚Äôs financials.) 
That growth will no doubt be challenged by Snapchat parent company, Snap, which is gearing up for an IPO this year. Snapchat had the original Stories product and has emerged as Instagram‚Äôs largest (and really only) major threat.
Instagram just recently started selling the same type of full screen, vertical video ads that Snapchat has popularized, and the two apps will be fighting to win marketer budgets. 
And, of course, fighting for your selfies and messages, too. 
‚ÄúOur mission is to strengthen relationships through shared experiences,‚Äù Systrom said. ‚ÄúAnd we‚Äôre going to be best at that in the world.‚Äù 

* Among those hired by Instagram in 2016 was my fianc√©e, whom I‚Äôve been with for seven years. She took a job as an administrative assistant with Instagram's marketing and community teams in June; you can read my full disclosure here. 






